    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_410236138" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/410236138" />
    <a title="Jacob" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/901342-jacob"><img alt="Jacob" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1555491633p2/901342.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/410236138?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jacob" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jacob" href="/user/show/901342-jacob">Jacob</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780805075205" href="/book/show/584668.The_Science_of_Good_and_Evil">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/901342-jacob?shelf=psychology">psychology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/901342-jacob?shelf=from_library">from_library</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/901342-jacob?shelf=science">science</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/901342-jacob?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer410236138" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1715156537482133634">I will admit to only reading 70% (through chapter 6) of this before calling it quits. I&apos;m not sure there could be a book less suited to my taste: a book which claims to fit with religion while repeatedly denigrating the existence of God, leaning almost entirely on evolutionary biology to tell stories about why moral feelings developed in humans, and above all no actual scientific explanation for why people cheat, gossip, care, share, and follow the Golden Rule. In a book called &quot;The Science of&quot; </span>
  <span id="freeText1715156537482133634" style="display:none">I will admit to only reading 70% (through chapter 6) of this before calling it quits. I'm not sure there could be a book less suited to my taste: a book which claims to fit with religion while repeatedly denigrating the existence of God, leaning almost entirely on evolutionary biology to tell stories about why moral feelings developed in humans, and above all no actual scientific explanation for why people cheat, gossip, care, share, and follow the Golden Rule. In a book called "The Science of" and subtitled "Why People Cheat, Gossip, Care, Share and Follow the Golden Rule", you might understand my disappointment.<br /><br />I could go on about the author's ranting over media pundits, or the academic language (not unique to this book, but still hard to read), but it's not worth the time. Suffice it to say the author's claim is that he's developed a moral system which is independent of religion and not absolute or external, but is not relativistic because he renamed it "provisional" and because he's pretty sure people will follow it because of their inherent evolutionarily-developed moral sense. Most of the time, anyway. Probably.<br /><br />The seven myths of evil the author references were interesting and helpful, although they were someone else's work. He's on solid ground in debunking the myth of the noble/beautiful and ecologically-respecting savage, although the application to the subject of the book is minimal. Other than that, he's a fan of fuzzy logic and explains everything with the claim that all individuals have both good AND evil in them, which is really not a reason why people do good or bad things. Also the "lack of technology" argument for free will -- that we have free will because we simply cannot track all the factors which determine our choices for us -- is weak. Any "lack of technology" argument is.<br /><br />A much better discussion of why people do bad things can be found in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1422244.Evil_Genes_Why_Rome_Fell__Hitler_Rose__Enron_Failed__and_My_Sister_Stole_My_Mother_s_Boyfriend" title="Evil Genes Why Rome Fell, Hitler Rose, Enron Failed, and My Sister Stole My Mother's Boyfriend by Barbara Oakley" rel="nofollow noopener">Evil Genes: Why Rome Fell, Hitler Rose, Enron Failed, and My Sister Stole My Mother's Boyfriend</a>. And even though I already got it from the library, I think I'll skip <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/89281.Why_People_Believe_Weird_Things_Pseudoscience__Superstition__and_Other_Confusions_of_Our_Time" title="Why People Believe Weird Things Pseudoscience, Superstition, and Other Confusions of Our Time by Michael Shermer" rel="nofollow noopener">Why People Believe Weird Things: Pseudoscience, Superstition, and Other Confusions of Our Time</a> by the same author as this book, which from some reviews has the same problem of not addressing the title issue, i.e. not explaining why people believe weird things.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1715156537482133634" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

