<div id="review_108220889" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/108220889" />
    <a title="Marnie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3817450-marnie"><img alt="Marnie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1516300622p2/3817450.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/108220889?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marnie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marnie" href="/user/show/3817450-marnie">Marnie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer108220889" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13683584122284292126">In debates of morality and human history, it&apos;s not uncommon for people to begin to wonder if humans are inherently good or inherently bad; if society is the only thing keeping us all from reenacting <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7624.Lord_of_the_Flies' title='Lord of the Flies by William Golding' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Lord of the Flies</a> or if big brother is simply taxing and legislating us instead of letting us act in the charitable way we would have otherwise. Each of us has been alive for such a short time in relation to human history and our respective societies have evolved to be so complex -- intertwining </span>
  <span id="freeText13683584122284292126" style="display:none">In debates of morality and human history, it's not uncommon for people to begin to wonder if humans are inherently good or inherently bad; if society is the only thing keeping us all from reenacting <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7624.Lord_of_the_Flies" title="Lord of the Flies by William Golding" rel="nofollow noopener">The Lord of the Flies</a> or if big brother is simply taxing and legislating us instead of letting us act in the charitable way we would have otherwise. Each of us has been alive for such a short time in relation to human history and our respective societies have evolved to be so complex -- intertwining with religion and local cultures and governments -- it can be hard to know where one's societal influences end and one's instincts pick up.<br /><br />This book is a fascinating scientific study of the roots of human morality. It lays out a case for how a person can be seemingly altruistic at one moment yet self-serving and greedy (or worse) in the next. Where the individual is compelled on one level to best serve himself, on another level, there is a biological imperative to also do what's best for the tribe/community/society/species, and this book explains why.<br /><br />We begin to see that trying to frame someone as pure good or pure evil, as we are wont to do with historic figures, only serves to blur our understanding of human behavior. Each of us is capable of both great and terrible behavior and this book can help us understand why.<br /><br />Despite the rather heavy topic and scientific nature of the book, I found Shermer's style easily accessible and entertaining to read. For folks who find topics of psychology, anthropology, morality and ethics and evolution interesting, or for people who want to reconcile how otherwise seemingly everyday people can act out in magnificent or atrocious ways, I think you'll find this book thought provoking.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13683584122284292126" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

